public class [name]{

   int num;
   //each class has a constructor
   public [name]((parameters),int num){
      this.num = num; //this. is used so the num in the parameter doesn't get confused with the original num for the class
      return;   //for the class constructor, the return doesn't need a type like int,String,char
   }

   //arrays :()
int[] hi = {5,1,2}; //starts with 0, can only be one type
String[] smirk = new String[5]; //creates empty table with 5 indexes, the size of the array cannot be changed
smirk = new String[2]; //smirk.length would be 2 cuz i changed it to empty table with 2 indexes :3,
//this new concept also works with other types -> String hi = New String("eff"); -> Integer hi = New Integer(1); //notice how it's Integer and not int (Integer is the "class" version of int)

   //you can rename the string classes return with toString()
   public String toString(){
      return "hi";
      //instead of returning [name]@2ffjy2344, it will return "hi" when the class is printed
   }

   //functions :D
   static public int getnum(){  //IMPORTANT: PURPOSE OF STATIC, without it, a class would have be made before this method could be called (works with variables 					//too) for example, getnum() would be a valid with static, without it, yes.getnum() is required
      return num;
   }
	
   //glorified if/else cant do conditionals (num>1) etc
   switch(num){
      case 1:
      break;
      case -1:
      break;
      case 0:
      break;
      default:
      //print num is neither 1, -1, nor 0
   }

   //each class has a main() method tht does stuffs, like execute methods, but none is created there
   public static void main(String[] args){
      [name] yes = New [name]((parameters),2);
      if(yes.num==yes.getnum()){
         System.out.println(yes); //should print out "hi"
      }
      for(int i=1;i<10;i++){ //i can be double too
         System.out.println(i);
      {
   }
}




[[[Terminal]]]

javac [name].java //this compiles the code and shows u the errors n stuff
java [name] args[0] args[1] args[...](arguments in the main() method - normally empty) //this runs the code
//in the editor you check if the args are equal to something with args[...].equals(x);



[[[useful stuffs]]]
.equals() checks if both objects contain the same values, whereas == takes it as face value, checking if the objects are the same
Integer = int, String = String, Char = char, Double = double, Boolean = boolean
\t is tab \n is new line //(relating to Strings)
; only goes at the end of a line, for ex print(add(1,2);); will error, print(add(1,2)); wont :)
Integer.parseInt(""); turns string to int
Integer.valueOf(""); turns string to Integer object //vice versa too
i+=1 is the same as i=i+1, works for other math operations  ie. i/=2, works for strings too :O
a++; adds 1 a--; subtracts 1 //can be used outside of for loop
System.currentTimeMillis() returns the time 
final int i = 1; //makes it so that i cannot be changed to any other variable
Math.random(); //returns random double 0-.99...  trick: (int)(-100*Math.random()+50) returns a random number between -50,50 trick:
Math.pow(base,power); //returns base^power 
replaced = "ah haha".replace("a","b") //replaced = "bh hbhb"
int a = (int)1.5; -> 1
int/double = int, unless cast (double)int/double = double
double a = 1.5; int b = a.IntValue();
